An Analysis of Hate Crimes and Social Media
By Nicholas Aoki, Jayoung Kim, and Elizabeth Steinbach (Group 2)

1. Introduction¶

Hate crimes, or "crime[s] motivated by bias against race, religion, national origin, sexual orientation, gender, gender identity, or disability" [1] have been rising in the United States [2, 3]. Given this increase in hate crimes, analyzing hate crime data and assessing how other factors, such as political affiliation and social media usage, may contribute to the problem are important as they may inform policymakers about how to mitigate this rise in hate crimes.

There are three overarching goals of this study: (a) to conduct an exploratory data analysis on hate crime data to better understand how the nature and target of hate crimes have changed over time; (b) to test whether political affiliation is related to the geographical distribution of hate crimes; (c) to analyze social media posts using natural language processing techniques in order to figure out the connections between hateful rhetoric online and hate crimes.

To narrow the scope of our analysis, we will specifically be investigating hate crimes in California from 2001 to 2020. Our specific questions are as follows:

  1. How have the number of hate crimes changed over time?
  2. Which types of hate crimes are the most common? How have the types of hate crimes changed over time?
  3. Which racial and religious groups tend to be the most targeted?
  4. How is county political affiliation related to the geographical distribution of hate crimes?
  5. How does the distribution of the types of hateful social media posts compare to the types of hate crimes?

This report is structured as follows. There are five parts after the Introduction. The first part ("Results: Exploratory Data Analysis") contains responses to the first three questions (1, 2, 3). The second part ("Results: Political Affiliation and Hate Crimes") answers Question 4, and the third part ("Results: Social Media Posts") responds to Question 5. Each of these three parts are further divided into subsections, and a description of these subsections is provided at the beginning of each part. The fourth part discusses the limitations of this study and offers a conclusion where a summary of the major findings can be found. The fifth part includes the references.

The analysis in this report draws on the topics covered in the lectures from the "Week_1-1" notebook to the "Week_3-2" notebook as well as the lectures from the natural language processing unit ("Week_6-1" to "Week_7-1"). In terms of extra credit, we have (a) employed statistical analysis by conducting a correlational analysis (see "Results: Political Affiliation and Hate Crimes"); (b) employed GeoPandas, a package that was not covered in class, to visualize the geographical distribution of hate crimes (see "Results: Political Affiliation and Hate Crimes"), and (c) used multiple data sets to answer the research questions. More specifically, we have employed eight data sets with the following information: (1) hate crimes in California from 2001 to 2020; (2) metadata with number of each county; (3) population data from California from 2000 to 2009; (4) population data from California from 2010 to 2019; (5) a shapefile with California county boundaries; (6) voter registration data for California counties in 2008; (7) voter registration data for California counties in 2016; (8) social media posts from Stormfront, a right-wing social media site. All of these data sets are reputable (i.e., they are all either from government sources or from journal articles). The contents of each data set are described in more detail in the section where they are first employed. Links to all data sets can be found in the "References" section.

2. Results: Exploratory Data Analysis¶

This section is subdivided into four parts. In the first part, the hate crimes data set is inspected and described. The next three parts answer the first three questions in the Introduction in order: (1) How have the number of hate crimes changed over time?; (2) Which types of hate crimes are the most common? How have the types of hate crimes changed over time?; (3) Which racial and religious groups tend to be the most targeted?.

2.1 Inspecting the Hate Crimes Data Set¶

The hate crimes data set comes from the data portal of the State of California Department of Justice [4]. The data set has 24436 rows and 23 columns (Block 2), where each row corresponds to a unique hate crime committed in California from 2001 to 2020. The column names (shown in Block 3) include information about each crime. The specific columns that will be used in this report ("ClosedYear", "County", "MostSeriousBiasType", and "MostSeriousBias") are shown in Block 4. The first two columns, "ClosedYear" and "County", indicate the year when the crime occurred and the county where the crime occurrred. The third column, "MostSeriousBiasType", classifies the crimes in terms of broad categories about the motivation of the crimes (e.g., whether the crime was committed because of a bias against a particular race/ethnicity/ancestry or against a particular sexual orientation, etc.). The fourth column, "MostSeriousBias", provides more detail about the specific social group that was targeted. For example, among the crimes committed because of a bias against race/ethnicity/ancestry, was the targeted social group Black or Hispanic?

Although we have narrowed the scope of our analysis to these four columns, we note that there are other aspects of the hate crimes in the data set that could also be explored (e.g., "MonthOccurrence" contains the month when the hate crimes occurred). We leave this analysis for future research.

Before moving on to the rest of the exploratory data analysis, the types of the columns were examined (Block 5). The type of the "ClosedYear" column was changed from "int64" to "object" (Block 6) so that the hate crimes could be grouped by year.

2.2 How have the number of hate crimes changed over time?¶

The first step of the exploratory analysis was to visualize how the number of hate crimes has changed over time in California from 2001 to 2020. The code in Block 7 groups the data by year and tabulates the number of crimes in each year, while Block 8 visualizes the data. The number of hate crimes was at its peak in 2001. Although the number of crimes steadily dropped from 2001 to 2014, the number of crimes increased from 2014 to 2020. Therefore, hate crimes have become a more pressing issue in California as of late (although the number of hate crimes in 2020 is still much lower than that in 2001).

In [7]:

2.3 Which types of hate crimes are the most common? How have the types of hate crimes changed over time?¶

Block 9 shows the number of hate crimes by type in the data set. There are six unique types that are listed: "Race/Ethnicity/Ancestry", "Sexual Orientation, "Religion", "Gender Nonconforming", "Disability", and "Gender". The crimes against race/ethnicity/ancestry predominate (60.1%), followed by crimes against sexual orientation (21.1%) and religion (16.5%), and then by crimes related to gender or disability. Note that in this data frame (and in subsequent data frames), proportions may not add up to 1 because the proportions are being rounded.

To visualize these counts, a pie chart is created (Block 11). To prevent slices in the pie chart from being too small, the counts corresponding to "Gender Nonconforming", "Disability", and "Gender" are combined into one category, "Gender/Disability" (Block 10).

A line plot displaying the number of hate crimes corresponding to "Race/Ethnicity/Ancestry", "Sexual Orientation", and "Gender" is shown in Block 13 (the data frame used to create this line plot is given in Block 12). The data for the gender/disability-related hate crimes were omitted from the graph given that their overall count was relatively low relative to the other types of crimes. The number of hate crimes against sexual orientation and gender has remained relatively unchanged over time and is consistently lower than the number of hate crimes against race/ethnicity/ancestry for every year in the data set. The number of hate crimes against race/ethnicity/ancestry is clearly driving the temporal pattern in Block 8 in that it has decreased from 2001 to 2014 and increased from 2014 to 2020. This makes sense given that the number of crimes of this type make up the largest proportion of crimes in the data set.

2.4 Which racial and religious groups tend to be the most targeted?¶

Block 14 shows the number of hate crimes by race among the hate crimes motivated by a bias against race/ethnicity/ancestry in the data set. There are ten unique types. Among the crimes committed against a known race in a single marked category (i.e., excluding the third, sixth, and ninth rows in the data frame shown in Block 14), the crimes against black or African American individuals make up more than half of the racially motivated hate crimes (51.1%), followed by anti-Hispanic or Latino crimes (16.4%), anti-White crimes (7.9%), anti-Asian crimes (6.1%), anti-Arab crimes (2.4%), anti-American Indian or Alaska Native crimes (0.4%), and anti-Native Hawaiian or Pacific Islander crimes (0.1%).

To visualize these counts, a pie chart is created (Block 16). The crimes against unknown or multiple races or against races with relatively few crimes (American Indian/Alaska Native and Native Hawaiian/Pacific Islander) are combined into one category, called "Other" (Block 15).

A line plot displaying the number of hate crimes for the four most commonly targeted races is shown in Block 18 (the data frame used to create this line plot is given in Block 17). One can see that the number of crimes against black or African American citizens in California is much higher than that against the other four races for every year from 2001 to 2020. The number of crimes against Hispanic and Latino people is slightly but consistently higher than those against White and Asian people, and the number of crimes against the latter two groups are fairly similar over time.

The number of hate crimes against black or African American people dipped from 2001 to 2014 and rose from 2014 to 2020, thus reflecting the temporal pattern of all race/ethnicity/ancestry-related crimes in Block 13. Although the number of hate crimes against the other three races has remained relatively constant over this time period, crimes against all three showed an uptick from 2019 to 2020.

Block 19 shows the number of hate crimes by each religion among the hate crimes motivated by a bias against religion in the data set. There are fourteen unique types. Among the crimes committed against a known religion, the two most common types are those against Jewish people (63.5%) and Muslim people (12.1%).

To visualize these counts, a pie chart is created (Block 21). The crimes against Christian religions of different denominations are combined into one category called "Christian" for visualization purposes. The other religions ("Anti-Sikh", "Anti-Hindu", "Anti-Atheism-Agnosticism", and "Anti-Buddhist") are combined with the "Anti-Other Religion" and "Anti-Multiple Religions (Group)" categories to create a single category called "Other" (Block 20).

A line plot displaying the number of hate crimes for the two most commonly targeted religions is shown in Block 23 (the data frame used to create this line plot is given in Block 22). The number of crimes against Jewish people rose dramatically in 2008, and although the number of crimes against Jews decreased afterwards, it has been rising since 2013. The number of crimes against Muslims has remained stable over time. The high number of crimes against Muslims in 2001 potentially reflects negative attitudes against Muslims in the wake of 9/11 [5].

plt.legend(prop={'size': 14})
plt.show()

3. Results: How is county political affiliation related to the geographical distribution of hate crimes?¶

In terms of the relationship between county political affiliation and the geographical distribution of hate crimes, our specific hypothesis is that counties with a higher proportion of registered Republican voters should have a greater number of hate crimes (relative to the population of each county). Given that negative attitudes towards minoritized social groups have been argued to be connected with the perpetration of hate crimes [6] and that Republicans tend to have more negative attitudes against minoritized social groups [7], it is possible that the distribution of hate crimes may be predicted by voter registration data.

This analysis is divided into two parts: (a) "Data Cleaning" and (b) "Analysis". The "Data Cleaning" section is further subdivided into the five steps that were taken to organize the data. The "Analysis" section contains the results. The relationship between county political affiliation and the geographical distribution of hate crimes is displayed for both 2008 and 2016 to illustrate the difference between the beginning of Obama's presidency and Trump's presidency.

The goal for the "Data Cleaning" section is to create a data set with the following features: (a) the geometric coordinates of the counties (geometry); (b) the number of hate crimes per one million people in 2008 and 2016 (Prop_2008 and Prop_2016); (c) the proportion of Republican voters in 2008 and 2016 (Prop_Rep_2008 and Prop_Rep_2016). The reason why there are so many steps is because six data sets were needed to answer these questions and they all had to be formatted so that they could be merged together properly.

3.1 Data Cleaning¶

Step 1: Create a data frame with the population of each county in California from 2001 to 2019.

Two data sets with information about the population of California counties were downloaded from the United States Census Bureau website [8]. The first had population data from 2001 to 2009 and the second contained population data from 2010 to 2019. Therefore, in order to create a data frame with the population of each county in California from 2001 to 2019, the two data sets had to be cleaned separately and then merged. Both data sets are organized such that each row refers to a unique county in California and each column after the first one refers to the population of the counties in a particular year (which is specified by the name of the column).

The data set with population data from 2001 to 2009 is shown in Block 24. In Block 28, the two population data sets are merged on the "County" column (only the column names are shown for brevity). Finally, Block 29 subsets the data for the years of interest: 2008 and 2016.

One of the goals of this section is to calculate the number of hate crimes per million people in each county, meaning that the number of hate crimes in each county has to be divided by the population of each county and multiplied by one million. In order to complete this calculation, the columns corresponding to the populations of each year have to be of the "int64" or "float64" type. However, all of the types of the columns are "object", as shown in Block 30. In order to change the types of the columns, the commas are first removed from all of the values corresponding to population numbers (Block 31) and then all of the columns are changed to the "int64" type (Block 32).

Step 3: Create a data set with the number of hate crimes in each county for the years 2008 and 2016.

Block 35 shows the total number of hate crimes per year for each county. Even from looking at the first few rows, one can see that certain counties are missing (e.g., there is no row corresponding to the year 2008 and the second county number). This is because there were no hate crimes for those particular combinations of year and county number (e.g., there were zero hate crimes in 2008 in the second county).

The code in Blocks 36 and 37 shows how these missing rows were added to the data set. Block 36 contains a list of the years of interest ("2008" and "2016") and the county numbers (1 to 58). The product of the years and county numbers if found and saved in a list. The product() is a "combinatoric iterator" from the itertools package that finds the Cartesian product of two lists (see the documentation here). The Cartesian product of two lists represents every possible tuple such that the first element is from the first list and the second element is from the second list. In this case, the first four tuples would be ("2008", 1), ("2008", 2), ("2008", 3), and ("2008", 4). The total number of tuples in the Cartesian product equals the length of the first list multiplied by the length of the second list (here, 2 years * 58 county numbers = 116 tuples).

The code in Block 37 loops through each of the tuples in year_numbers_combo. If there is no row corresponding to a particular tuple, then a new row is created in hate_by_county_year with the year and county number of that tuple and a value of 0 for the Count column. This new row is then added as the last row of the data set. The last few rows of hate_by_county_year are shown in Block 37 after the for loop. As shown in Block 38, the number of rows equals 116, which is the same as the number of tuples (thus indicating that the for loop worked as expected).

Finally, the hate_by_county_year data set is merged with the population data set, pop on the County_Number column (Block 39). Each row in the new merged data set, hate_by_county_year_pop, corresponds to a unique county-year combination and contains the population on 2008 and 2016 as well as the county number and the number of hate crimes in each year for each county.

In Block 40, a separate data set called hate_2008 is created by subsetting only the rows where the year equals 2008. The number of hate crimes in 2008 per one million people in each county is calculated in Block 41. The code in Block 42 does the same thing for the hate crimes in 2016.

3.2 Analysis¶

The maps in Block 50 and 51 below show the proportion of hate crimes per one million people in 2008 and the proportion of hate crimes per one million people in 2016, respectively. In both of the maps, there does not seem to be a noticeable pattern about where the hate crimes tend to be concentrated as there are counties with a high proportion of hate crimes in all parts of the state.

The maps in Block 52 and 53 below show the percentage of Republican voters by county in 2008 and in 2016, respectively. The fact that the highest value on the scale for both maps is 50% or below shows that the majority of voters in all of the counties are registered as non-Republicans (Democrats, Independents, etc.). There is a clear pattern such that the counties with the highest proportion of registered Republicans are in the Central Valley and the counties with the lowest proportion are in the urban areas along the coast (e.g., near San Francisco, Los Angeles, etc.).

The code in Block 54 calculates the correlation between the proportion of hate crimes per one million people in 2008 and the percentage of Republican voters by county in 2008, and the code in Block 55 calculates the correlation between the proportion of hate crimes per one million people in 2016 and the percentage of Republican voters by county in 2016. The scatterplots for 2008 and 2016 are visualized in Blocks 56 and 57, respectively with regression lines placed on top of the scatterplots.

The correlation between the proportion of hate crimes per one million people in 2016 and the percentage of Republican voters by county in 2016 is significantly negative (p = 0.003) while the correlation between the proportion of hate crimes per one million people in 2008 and the percentage of Republican voters by county in 2008 is non-significant (p = 0.076) with a significance level of 0.05 (although the correlation is similarly negative). This indicates that there is evidence in 2016 that counties with a higher percentage of Republican voters tended to have fewer hate crimes per one million people.

One can see that the scatterplot for 2008 (Block 56) has several clear outliers corresponding to counties where the number of hate crimes per one million people was greater than 100. Even when these outliers are removed, the correlation between the proportion of hate crimes per one million people in 2008 and the percentage of Republican voters by county in 2008 is still non-significant (p = 0.144).

4. Results: How does the distribution of the types of hateful social media posts compare to the types of hate crimes?¶

Given that racist and prejudiced rhetoric proliferates on social media platforms [10, 11] and that some scholars have argued that social media usage and hate crimes are interconnected [12], an analysis of hateful speech online represents a fitting complement to our study of hate crime data. Our hypothesis is as follows: If hateful social media posts are tagged in a similar way to the hate crimes in the crime data set (i.e., as relating to either race/ethnicity/ancestry, sexual orientation, religion, or gender/disability), then the distribution of the types of social media posts should be similar to the distribution of the types of hate crimes. More specifically, it was noted earlier that among hate crimes committed in California from 2001 to 2020, "[t]he crimes against race/ethnicity/ancestry predominate (60.1%), followed by crimes against sexual orientation (21.1%) and religion (16.5%), and then by crimes related to gender or disability" (see the section titled "Which types of hate crimes are the most common? How have the types of hate crimes changed over time?" above). Therefore, we predict that the distribution of hateful social media posts should match the distribution of hate crime types (i.e., hateful posts about race should represent the majority of posts with posts about sexual orientation and religion being the second and third most common and with posts about gender or disability being the least common of the four types).

This section is divided into two parts: (a) "Data Cleaning" and (b) "Analysis". The "Data Cleaning" section is further subdivided into two parts. In "Step 1", a corpus of hateful tweets is created from a series of txt files and in "Step 2", the corpus is tokenized and lemmatized. The "Analysis" section contains the response to the question of interest.

4.1 Data Cleaning¶

Step 1: Create a corpus of hateful social media posts.

The corpus of hateful social media posts in this study comes from a series of posts from 2002 to 2017 on Stormfont, a right-wing social media site [13]. The creators in [13] have organized the posts as follows. First, a directory called "all_files" contains a series of text files. Each text file contains a unique post and the name of the text file represents the identification number of the post. Each row in a separate csv file called "annotations_metadata.csv" corresponds to a particular post, and the values in a column called "file_id" correspond to the identification numbers of the text files. In the csv file, each post is labelled as being either hateful ("hate") or as not hateful ("noHate"). The labelling was decided subjectively by the authors in [13]. The goal of this step is to select all of the posts that are tagged as being hateful and to concatenate them all into one string that can be analyzed with the natural language processing techniques that we have learned.

The "annotations_metadata.csv" file is loaded in Block 59 and the columns of interest (the file identification numbers and the labelling) are selected in Block 60. There are no null values in the csv file (Block 61), and one can see that there around 1196 posts that have been tagged as being hateful (Block 62). Block 63 changes the categorical labels to numeric values (with "hate" being changed to 1), and Block 64 saves all of the rows with hateful posts in a data frame called "hate".

Block 65 turns the "file_id" column into a list, and Block 66 adds ".txt" to the end of every file identification number. Block 67 loads the posts from the "all_files" directory. Block 68 appends the txt files from "all_files" to a list for all of the file names in Block 66 (i.e., the list called "corpus" in Block 68 contains only the files with hateful posts). The corpus is not shown here to prevent this report from becoming overly lengthy.

Step 2: Tokenize and lemmatize the corpus.

Block 69 converts the list called "corpus" to a string. The string is tokenized by word in Block 70, the punctuation is removed in Block 71, and the string is lowercased in Block 72. After creating a lemmatizer with nltk (Block 73) and defining a function to convert the Brown part of speech tags to the WordNet part of speech tags (Block 74), the first few tags are inspected (Block 75). Words with tags pertatining to non-functional words (e.g., determiners or DET) are removed (Block 76) and the words are then lemmatized (Block 77). The English stop words from nltk are loaded (Block 78), but a new list of stop words is created in Block 79. As the pre-defined list of stop words in nltk only contains words that are spelled correctly, it cannot remove stop words that are spelled incorrectly (e.g., "wouldn'" instead of "wouldn't"). Given that this corpus is composed of posts on the Internet, which often contain typos, it was necessary to create a customized list of stop words. Block 80 removes all of the stop words from the corpus using this customized list.

# Define a function to change the tag labels
def wordnet_pos(tag):
    """Map a Brown POS tag to a WordNet POS tag."""
    
    table = {"N": wordnet.NOUN, "V": wordnet.VERB, "R": wordnet.ADV, "J": wordnet.ADJ}
    
    # Default to a noun.
    return table.get(tag[0], wordnet.NOUN)

4.2 Analysis¶

Block 81 saves the frequency distribution of the words in "fq", and Block 82 shows the most common words. One can see that the most common nouns are related to either race (e.g., "white", "black", "race", "negro") or to religion ("jew"). This corroborates with the analysis in the hate crimes data set as black people are the most heavily targeted racial group (see Block 16 above) and Jews are the most heavily targeted religious group (see Block 21 above).

Block 83 defines four lists which contain words corresponding to each of the four types of hate crimes in the California hate crimes data set (the words in each list were determined subjectively by the group members). Blocks 84, 85, 86, and 87 show the frequency distribution of the words categorized as pertaining to "Race/Ethnicity/Ancestry", of the words categorized as pertaining to "Religion", of the words categorized as pertaining to "Sexual Orientation", and of the words categorized as pertaining to "Gender/Disability", respectively. As noted earlier, the most common racially-related words are "white" and "black" (Block 84). The most common religions that are mentioned in Block 85 are "jew" and "muslim", which corresponds to the two most commonly targeted religions in the hate crimes data set (Block 21). Finally, we note that "woman" and "girl" are the most common words among those pertaining to gender/disability.

Block 88 counts the number of words in each of the four frequency distributions, and Block 89 creates a data frame with these counts. Block 90 shows a pie chart with the relative proportion of words in each of the four categories. In accord with the hypothesis stated above, the words pertaining to "Race/Ethnicity/Ancestry" make up the majority of the corpus (73.9%), similar to how majority of crimes in the hate crimes data set are motivated by "Race/Ethnicity/Ancestry" (60.1%). However, the proportion of words pertaining to "Gender/Disability" make up more of the corpus of social media posts (12.3%) compared to the proportion of hate crimes pertaining to "Gender/Disability" (2.2%).

Conclusion¶

There were three goals of this study: (a) to conduct an exploratory data analysis on hate crime data to better understand how the nature and target of hate crimes have changed over time; (b) to test whether political affiliation is related to the geographical distribution of hate crimes; (c) to analyze social media posts using natural language processing techniques in order to figure out the connections between hateful rhetoric online and hate crimes. Our two primary data sets were a hate crimes data set with crimes in California from 2001 to 2020 and a data set with social media posts on Stormfront, a right-wing social media site. Our specific questions were as follows:

  1. How have the number of hate crimes changed over time?
  2. Which types of hate crimes are the most common? How have the types of hate crimes changed over time?
  3. Which racial and religious groups tend to be the most targeted?
  4. How is county political affiliation related to the geographical distribution of hate crimes?
  5. How does the distribution of the types of hateful social media posts compare to the types of hate crimes?

Section 2 ("Results: Exploratory Data Analysis") responded to the first three questions. In response to the first question, we found that the number of hate crimes in California were at their highest in 2001, and although the number of crimes decreased from 2001 to 2014, the number has been rising ever since. This supports claims that hate crimes are rising in the United States [2, 3].

In response to the second question, we observed that hate crimes motivated by a bias against race/ethnicity/ancestry were most common overall in California. This was followed by crimes against particular religions or sexual orientations. Crimes targeted a particular gender or disability were the least common among the four types. Although the crimes against religion and sexual orientation have remained relatively constant over time, those against race/ethnicity/ancestry have fluctuated.

In response to the third question, we showed that among the racial groups that were targeted, blacks or African Americans tend to be the most targeted. Moreover, among the religious groups that were targeted, Jews and Muslims tend to be the most targeted.

Section 3 ("Results: How is county political affiliation related to the geographical distribution of hate crimes?") answered the fourth question. Our specific hypothesis was as follows: counties with a higher proportion of registered Republican voters should have a greater number of hate crimes (relative to the population of each county). We actually found that in 2008, there was no evidence of a relationship between the number of hate crimes and the proportion of Republican voters, and that in 2016, there was a negative correlation between the number of hate crimes and the proportion of Republican voters. In other words, counties with a higher proportion of registered Republican voters in 2016 had a lower number of hate crimes in the same year, which went against out hypothesis.

Given that Republican voters tend to be less commonly found in urban areas [14] and that urban areas generally have higher crime rates overall [15], it is possible that the number of hate crimes in a particular county is more related to whether the county is in an urban or rural setting rather than the voter registration statistics, as we had hypothesized.

Section 4 ("Results: How does the distribution of the types of hateful social media posts compare to the types of hate crimes?") answered the fifth question. We predicted that the distribution of hateful social media posts should match the distribution of hate crime types (i.e., hateful posts about race should represent the majority of posts with posts about sexual orientation and religion being the second and third most common and with posts about gender or disability being the least common of the four types). This hypothesis was largely confirmed in the analysis given that hateful posts about race represented the majority of posts in the Stormfront corpus and that hate crimes targeting a particular race/etnicity represented the majority of crimes in the crimes data set.

We note that there are several limitations to the current study. First, hate crimes are often underreported [16], meaning that the hate crimes data set from the California government may be incomplete. Second, each crime in the hate crimes data set was categorized as pertaining to a single category (e.g., as being motivated by either race/ethnicity/ancestry or by gender). However, social categories like race and gender are intersectional [17], so it is possible that people may have been targeted for being part of muliple minoritized groups (e.g., individuals may have harrassed a black woman for both her race and her gender). Finally, although it is interesting that the social media data set and the hate crimes data set matched in that most of the content had to do with race/ethnicity/ancestry, these results should be interpreted with caution as this analysis cannot provide evidence for a causal link between social media posts and crime.

By analyzing hate crime data and connecting this to other relevant issues, such as politics and social media, we believe that this analysis is potentially useful for better understanding the distribution of hate crimes and for ultimately helping to mitigate the rise in hate crimes that has been observed.
